Curiosity was launched from Cape Canaveral on November 26, 2011. It successfully landed on Aeolis Palus in Gale Crater on Mars on August 6, 2012.

The main goals of the mission were to determine if Mars could have once harbored life, to study geological and geochemical compositions and processes, to investigate long term planetary processes and to characterize the broad spectrum of surface radiation.
Curiosity is the size of a small car and is equipped with computers, cameras, communications and even a laser!

Sputnik 1 was the first artificial Earth satellite. It was launched during the International Geophysical Year from Site No. 1/5, at the 5th Tyuratam range in Kazach SSR in the former Soviet Union.

Many models of the original Sputnik 1 have been created and are on display in such institutions as the Smithsonian's National Air and Space Museum, the Science Museum, London and the World Museum in Liverpool.
Sputnik inspired a generation of engineers, scientists and astronauts and ushered in the beginning of the modern Space exploration era.
